<br>
My only question remains about the airport security matter.  You say you distrust statistics - ok.  But even just a cursory glance at the number of Islamist terrorists who have perpetrated acts of violence (especially in regards to airplane hijackings) indicates that 99% of them are of Arabic descent.  Actually, I'm not positive about the number, but let's assume that the figure is correct for the sake of argument, since I'm trying to make a theoretical point and not a practical one.  Would, then, an assumption regarding the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>probability</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that Person X is a terrorist be justified based upon their race?  I agree that it would be ridiculous to automatically assume that they are a terrorist if they're Arabic, but would it not simply make logical sense to look especially hard at those of Arabic descent?  If there is a statistically significant correlation between the two factors, wouldn't it make sense?  I actually think its impossible for political reasons if nothing else, but the problem remains.<br>
<br>
Loegan's only response to this argument was, &quot;Then they would send non-Arabs and fool us all!&quot;  Well, uh, you wouldn't just stop searching or investigating all non-Arabs.  And that's sidestepping the issue anyway.<br>
<br>
Interested in hearing what you think... <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com/sigs/caledhon.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=walkabout>Walkabout</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 475<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/21/03 10:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=632.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I'm a racist</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Anyways, let's make this simple. Do you automatically make certain assumptions when you first meet/see a person based upon their ethnicity? If so, then yes, I say that is racism.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Let's define one thing first, racism is discrimination based on race and race only (hence the word), I'm not aware of any word meaning discrimination based on ethnics (which encompass race, religion, language, culture etc and is a far narrower expression) although it probably exists. Discrimination simply means treating differently, although in the most common sense it means treating someone/thing worse than others.<br>
<br>
Prejudice - which is what I interpret your quote to describe - is not the same as racism. I'd argue that your life depend on prejudice-like decisions. A fundamental thing about us is we use recognition and patterns as part of our learning. If you got bitten by a snake as a kid, you're not going to approach the next snake as if it was your friend - you will recognize it as something possibly hostile and treat it as such. It may save your life at a later stage.<br>
<br>
Several/many studies has shown that good looking people are attributed better skills than they actually have, and e.g. overweight people are attributed worse skills than they have. During the first few seconds when you meet a &quot;new&quot; person you make up your opinion about that person, it's your &quot;gut&quot; feeling and it's dependant on many factors, of which race, language, religion, colour etc all may play a part.<br>
<br>
So while you, unconscious, make up your impression about a new person based on his/her ethnics, it's not racism. It's how the human brain works, it's how your brain automatically goes looking for similarities between this person and other persons you know or think you know, you try to find out as much as you can about this person based on knowledge you already possess from your encounters with others.<br>
<br>
Discrimination would be treating this person worse than others - based on your prejudice. <p><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><br>
When in doubt, feign and let the others die<br>
